{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d4bd8ab0-66e0-4892-af18-1c18efcbff23","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options available via `--auth`:\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with no auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n\n# With Azure AD single-org auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com\n\n# With Azure AD B2C\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth IndividualB2C\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for all options including `--use-controllers`, `--no-openapi`, and framework version flags.\n\nWant me to scaffold a project with a specific configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4661212e-e2a5-4274-bf3d-a106420728c7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":320,"requestId":"4049:13072B:24F0250:29B7FDC:69EC0E47"},"id":"cf9b192c-49f7-43f3-959d-7c97d9b199b8","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:43:59.465Z","parentId":"5e78e68b-6b84-45de-b17c-c53657bd1e76"}
